          "body": "This is the chapter's most perplexing law for modern readers. Two men are fighting; one man's wife intervenes to help her husband by seizing his opponent's genitals. The law prescribes cutting off her hand without pity. Several interpretive options circulate among orthodox commentators. Most straightforwardly, the law targets an action that poses a direct threat to the opponent's capacity for reproduction — in the context of levirate law and the entire chapter's concern with the preservation of male lineage and name, such an act strikes at the same concern the levirate law protects. Some commentators (Peter Craigie, *Deuteronomy*, NICOT) also note that the law limits the scope of permissible intervention in a fight: even well-intentioned help is bounded by what methods may be used. The phrase 'you shall not show pity' (*lo takhus enekha*) appears elsewhere in Deuteronomy only in the severest cases (13:8; 19:13, 21; 25:12), signaling that the offense is categorically serious. Whatever the specific ancient social rationale, the law insists that motive (defending one's husband) does not sanctify every method. Means are moral, not only ends."
