          "body": "The chapter — and effectively the entire Deuteronomic law code (chapters 12-26) — closes not with a cultic regulation but with a military-theological command. Amalek had attacked Israel in the wilderness at Rephidim (Exodus 17:8-16), specifically targeting the stragglers at the rear — the faint, the weary, the most vulnerable. Moses names two features of the attack: its predatory strategy (targeting the weak) and its theological root ('he did not fear God,' 25:18). The fear of God is the foundation of all the chapter's laws — the judge who limits stripes fears God; the brother who performs levirate duty fears God; the merchant who carries honest weights fears God. Amalek's attack was the systematic expression of a nation that does not. The command to 'blot out the memory of Amalek' (25:19) is Israel's holy war mandate against this anti-covenantal archetype. The double imperative — 'you shall blot out... you must not forget' — is the strongest rhetorical form in Hebrew: an active obligation confirmed by its negative counterpart. Saul's failure to execute this command in 1 Samuel 15 becomes the decisive crisis of his kingship; David executes campaigns against Amalek in 1 Samuel 27 and 30; Esther and Mordecai's story (cf. Esther 3:1, where Haman is identified as an Agagite, a descendant of Amalek's king) shows the command still reverberating centuries later. Theologically, Amalek functions in the canon as the embodiment of godless predation on the weak — the antithesis of everything Deuteronomy 25 commands."
