        "title": "Honest scales are a theological claim — commerce under covenantal scrutiny",
        "range": "25:13-16",
        "excerpt": "You shall have a full and just weight; you shall have a full and just measure, that your days may be prolonged in the land which the Lord your God gives you.",
        "body": "The weights-and-measures prohibition (25:13-16) moves from the courtroom and the family to the marketplace, but the ethical logic is identical: the covenant community must not use asymmetric power to extract from another what it will not honestly give. The merchant with two sets of weights does not steal by force; he steals by system — a heavier weight when buying (he receives more grain than he paid for) and a lighter weight when selling (his customer receives less grain than she paid for). The fraud is structural, embedded in the tools of the trade, invisible to the untrained eye.\n\nMoses's response is threefold. The prohibition is stated negatively: do not carry two sets (25:13-14). The positive command is stated with double emphasis: have a *shalem* (complete, whole, full) and *tsedeq* (righteous, just) weight; have a *shalem* and *tsedeq* measure (25:15). The motive clause is covenantal: the blessing of long tenure in the land YHWH gives depends on it. And the theological ground clause is the chapter's strongest: 'everyone who acts unjustly is an *abomination* (*toevah*) to the LORD your God' (25:16).\n\n*Toevah* is the language of categories — it marks something as falling outside the boundary of what is compatible with YHWH's character. It is used in Deuteronomy for idolatry (7:25-26), child sacrifice (12:31), sexual immorality (23:18), and defective sacrificial animals (17:1). Its application to dishonest weights places market fraud in the company of idolatry — not because they are identical, but because they share the same character: a refusal to honor God's claim on human action in favor of self-serving exploitation. Proverbs 11:1 ('A false balance is an abomination to the LORD, but a just weight is His delight') and Proverbs 20:10, 23 repeat the verdict; Amos 8:5 and Micah 6:10-11 show the prophets prosecuting Israel for violating it.\n\nThe principle extends beyond ancient Near Eastern commerce. Any system designed to receive more than it gives — any structure that benefits from information asymmetry, from the customer's or employee's inability to verify the measure — falls under the same verdict. The employer who shaves wages, the contractor who dilutes materials, the financial advisor who obscures fees: the tools are different; the *toevah* is the same.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Shalem* (full, whole, complete, 25:15) — the same root as *shalom*; honest weights are a form of peace, of wholeness. *Tsedeq* (just, righteous) — the cardinal Old Testament justice term; applied here not to courts but to measuring instruments. *Toevah* (abomination, 25:16) — occurs twenty-one times in Deuteronomy; its application here to commercial ethics is one of the most striking uses in the book."
